<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">18430861</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2008</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>03</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2013</Year><Month>05</Month><Day>20</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1546-3141</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>190</Volume><Issue>5</Issue><PubDate><Year>2008</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>AJR. American journal of roentgenology</Title><ISOAbbreviation>AJR Am J Roentgenol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>An introduction to the Fourier transform: relationship to MRI.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1396</StartPage><EndPage>1405</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1396-405</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.2214/AJR.07.2874</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">The Fourier transform, a fundamental mathematic tool widely used in signal analysis, is ubiquitous in radiology and integral to modern MR image formation. Understanding MRI techniques requires a basic understanding of what the Fourier transform accomplishes. MR image encoding, filling of k-space, and a wide spectrum of artifacts are all rooted in the Fourier transform.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">This article illustrates these basic Fourier principles and their relationship to MRI.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Gallagher</LastName><ForeName>Thomas A</ForeName><Initials>TA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Radiology, Loyola University Medical Center, 2160 S First Ave., Maywood, IL 60153, USA. tgalla1@lumc.edu</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Nemeth</LastName><ForeName>Alexander J</ForeName><Initials>AJ</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hacein-Bey</LastName><ForeName>Lotfi</F